Data drift can have multiple causes: 
o upstream process changes, such as the replacement of a sensor, 
the calibration of which differs slightly from that previously 
installed; 

o data quality problems, e.g. a broken sensor that would always 
indicate a zero value; 

o the natural drift of the data, such as the variation in average 
temperature over the seasons; 

o the appearance of a new category in a classification problem; 

o drift due to sudden changes, such as the loss of a system’s 
ability to detect faces following the massive wearing of masks 
during the Covid-19 outbreak; 

o changes in the relationship between characteristics; 

o malicious poisoning as part of continuous learning, which can 
for example be noticed by abnormal outcomes.

